===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|en|enm|spade}}, from {{inh|en|ang|spada}}, {{m|ang|spade}}, {{m|ang|spadu||spade}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*spadǭ}}, {{m|gem-pro|*spadô}}, {{m|gem-pro|*spadō||spade}}. Cognate with {{cog|nl|spade}}, {{cog|ofs|spada}}, {{cog|osx|spado}}, {{cog|de|Spaten}}, {{cog|hrx|Spaad}}. Ultimately from {{der|en|ine-pro|*sph₂-dʰ-}}, whence also {{cog|grc|σπάθη||blade}}, {{cog|hit|tr=išpatar|t=spear}}, {{cog|fa|سپار||plow|tr=sopār}}, {{cog|lrc|ئەسپار||digging|tr=aspār}} and {{cog|ckb|ئەسپەر}}, {{m|ckb|ئەسپەرە|t=cross-piece on shaft of spade to take pressure of foot}}.<ref>Dehkhoda dictionary: [https://www.parsi.wiki/fa/wiki/topicdetail/2e945191d4754cb6ab3fd8f3e99eacc2 سپار].</ref> The playing card sense is assimilated from Romance-language terms for "sword," as the suit is depicted in various decks, such as {{bor|en|it|spada}}. {{doublet|en|spatha|épée}}.

